        <tr> 
          <td><textarea name="textarea" cols="40" rows="30" readonly>Image 555

Although not a single example now survives, there is documentary evidence that Netherlandish altarpieces, of which this is a fragment, were popular in later medieval England and commissioned by English patrons from manufacturers in such centres of production as Antwerp. Made of painted wood and comparable in size to alabaster altarpieces like the Swansea Altarpiece (see Image 120), Netherlandish altarpieces were more highly gilded and coloured than native alabaster devotional panels. The present panel once formed part of a Passion of Christ altarpiece, in which it would have been positioned to the left of a central Crucifixion panel. On stylistic grounds it has been attributed to a Brussels workshop of the second half of the 15th century. (The panel was once in the collection of A.W. N. Pugin).

Boldrick, Park, Williamson 2002, 
pp.76-7
</textarea></td>
